## Understanding

Issue #74 asks to port four utility subcommands (`history`, `scan`, `vision`, `auth`) from `scripts/loop.sh` (bash) to TypeScript, plus create a `shell.ts` helper module. These are non-orchestration commands — safe, self-contained utilities that validate the CLI foundation before tackling the main loop engine. **No `src/` directory exists yet** — this is greenfield alongside issue #73 (CLI scaffold with `cli.ts`, `init`, `config.ts`, `logger.ts`). This issue assumes #73's scaffold is in place and builds on it.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `src/lib/shell.ts` exports `exec(cmd, opts?)` → returns stdout string, throws on non-zero exit with stderr
- [ ] `src/lib/shell.ts` exports `run(cmd, args, opts?)` → streams stdout/stderr, returns Promise\<number\> (exit code)
- [ ] Both `exec()` and `run()` respect `cwd` option
- [ ] `src/commands/history.ts` — `alpha-loop history` lists all sessions from `sessions/` by parsing `session.yaml` files
- [ ] `alpha-loop history <name>` shows session detail (name, date, repo, model, duration, issues table with status symbols)
- [ ] `alpha-loop history <name> --qa` prints contents of `sessions/<name>/qa-checklist.md`
- [ ] `alpha-loop history --clean` removes session directories older than 30 days
- [ ] History outputs graceful message when no sessions exist
- [ ] `src/commands/scan.ts` — `alpha-loop scan` invokes Claude CLI to generate `.alpha-loop/context.md`
- [ ] Scan overwrites existing context file on re-run
- [ ] `src/commands/vision.ts` — `alpha-loop vision` prompts interactively (7 questions) and saves to `.alpha-loop/vision.md`
- [ ] Vision skips gracefully when `!process.stdin.isTTY`
- [ ] Vision shows current vision and asks to update if `.alpha-loop/vision.md` already exists
- [ ] `src/commands/auth.ts` — `alpha-loop auth` checks for `playwright-cli`, shows error if missing
- [ ] Auth opens browser at configured app URL, saves state to `.alpha-loop/auth/`
- [ ] Auth adds `.alpha-loop/auth/` to `.gitignore` if not present
- [ ] All four commands registered in `src/cli.ts` and appear in `--help`
- [ ] `scripts/loop.sh` is not modified

## Implementation Plan

**Prerequisite assumption:** Issue #73 delivers `src/cli.ts` (Commander entrypoint), `src/commands/init.ts`, `src/lib/config.ts`, `src/lib/logger.ts`. If those don't exist yet, create minimal stubs.

### 1. Create `src/lib/shell.ts` — Shell execution helpers

```typescript
import { execSync, spawn } from 'node:child_process';
```

- `exec(cmd, opts?)`: wraps `execSync` with `encoding: 'utf-8'`, `stdio: ['pipe','pipe','pipe']`, returns `.trim()`, throws on non-zero (error includes stderr)
- `run(cmd, args, opts?)`: wraps `spawn`, pipes stdout/stderr line-by-line to optional callbacks, returns `Promise<number>` (exit code). Use `readline.createInterface` on each stream for line splitting.

### 2. Create `src/commands/history.ts`

Port all five bash functions (`run_history`, `history_list`, `history_show_detail`, `history_show_qa`, `history_clean`). 

Key design:
- Use the `yaml` package (already a dependency) to parse `sessions/*/session.yaml` — much cleaner than bash's line-by-line regex parsing
- Define a `SessionData` TypeScript interface: `{ name, repo, started, duration, model, issues: Array<{number, status, pr_url?, error?, duration?}> }`
- `historyList()`: glob `sessions/*/session.yaml`, parse each, sort by date descending, format table with `printf`-style padding (use `String.padEnd()`)
- `historyDetail(name)`: parse single session.yaml, display header fields + issues table with ✓/✗/⊘ symbols
- `historyQa(name)`: read and print `sessions/<name>/qa-checklist.md` via `fs.readFileSync`
- `historyClean()`: iterate sessions, parse `started` date, compare to 30-day cutoff, `fs.rmSync(dir, {recursive: true})`
- Commander registration: `.command('history [session]').option('--qa').option('--clean').action(historyCommand)`

### 3. Create `src/commands/scan.ts`

Port `generate_project_context()` (loop.sh:1086-1138).

- Create `.alpha-loop/` directory if needed (`fs.mkdirSync(dir, {recursive: true})`)
- Use `run()` from `shell.ts` to invoke `claude -p --model opus --dangerously-skip-permissions --output-format text` with the scan prompt piped to stdin
- Alternatively, use `exec()` with the scan prompt via echo pipe: `exec('echo "..." | claude -p ...')`
- Write output to `.alpha-loop/context.md`
- Show success/failure via logger
- Commander: `.command('scan').description('Generate project context').action(scanCommand)`

### 4. Create `src/commands/vision.ts`

Port `run_vision()` (loop.sh:868-1067).

- Use `node:readline` for interactive prompts (create a helper `ask(question): Promise<string>`)
- Check `process.stdin.isTTY` — if not interactive, print message and exit
- If `.alpha-loop/vision.md` exists, show it and ask if user wants to update
- 7 questions matching the bash implementation (project description, user type, stage, priority, UX guidelines, north star, additional context)
- For north star: if input is a number or GitHub issue URL, fetch via `exec('gh issue view ...')` 
- Synthesize via Claude CLI (same pattern as scan), with fallback to raw inputs if synthesis fails
- Save to `.alpha-loop/vision.md`
- Commander: `.command('vision').description('Set up project vision').action(visionCommand)`

### 5. Create `src/commands/auth.ts`

Port auth subcommand (loop.sh:3257-3319).

- Check `command -v playwright-cli` via try/catch on `exec('which playwright-cli')`
- Read config to get port (default 3000) for app URL
- Prompt user for custom URL via readline
- Use `run('playwright-cli', ['open', url, '--headed', '--persistent'])` to launch browser
- Wait for user to press Enter
- Attempt state save via `exec('playwright-cli state-save ...')`; fallback to cookie/localstorage export
- Kill browser process, cleanup
- Check `.gitignore` for `.alpha-loop/auth/`, append if missing
- Commander: `.command('auth').description('Save browser auth state').action(authCommand)`

### 6. Modify `src/cli.ts` — Register new commands

Add imports and registrations for all four new commands after the `init` command from #73:
```typescript
import { historyCommand } from './commands/history.js';
import { scanCommand } from './commands/scan.js';
import { visionCommand } from './commands/vision.js';
import { authCommand } from './commands/auth.js';
```

